description.text:
Changed a few parts in the original Fragmaster design, and created a motor mount for the Blackwidow 4110 motors with integrated ESC.

4110 Motor mount for 3D Printable DJI Inspire V1.5 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:909384/

Watch these motors in flight!! via Vidit360 panoramic 360 video playlist>> https://youtu.be/qSWhDTiPgjc
https://youtu.be/MlbaShxL3nw
https://youtu.be/Eh0JpmRoGT4
https://youtu.be/zmkWxsa_Sg4

360 video shot with this quad mobius camera I designed:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1884782

The camera is shock mounted to the DJI Inspire clone using this shock mount:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1900626

This motor mount part enables using newly available Black Widow 4110-460 motor with integrated 40A ESC. Excellent initial flight test results with these motors using 13" props ... rated for up to 15" props! This is a more powerful higher performance motor compared to other motors being used on this clone DJI Inspire quadcopter .. and the integrated ESC is a cleaner package that reserves electronics bay space. Motor center-line position is unchanged from the original mount part. Note: the 16mm carbon fiber tube must be notched, if motor wires are routed through the tube.

3W Star LED on aluminum heat sink ... FYI - these must be run on low voltage, or flashed on/off to keep from over heating (they blink and/or go dim when over heating). I used an Arduino ProMini along with LED driver to control blinking, very bright, but duty cycle is low enough to keep LEDs cool.

I modified the angled arm tube clamps, to better support the rotating carbon fiber tube, since there is a big hole in that tube for wiring. I also removed 2 of the screws from that clamp .. 8 screws was overkill.

I strengthened the frame portion where the geared servo mounts for lifting the arms .. the original was bending, and the original had a great deal of useless structure that provided no function (dead weight).

Part photos here were printed in PETG (eSUN brand), 0.2mm layer height, 0.6mm nozzle, 140mm/sec.

This is a big quad, about 6 to 7 times heavier than a 250 racing quad, and it will use at least 13" props. I used ecalc.ch/xcoptercalc.php to size my motors, ESC, Props, and battery for this machine .. see link to my build details below and summary of components used.

Toymaker Charles Crandall invented the game "Pigs in Clover" in 1889. While he waited for his patent, competitors brought out very similar versions of the game. Eventually, Crandall's game, produced at his Waverly Toy Works, enjoyed great success and became something of a best-seller. But similarly-named games made by his competitors took away some of his profits. Pigs in Clover became the subject of political cartoons and rumor said that even President Harrison played the game. -- Museum of Play

It should help with pulling the cap out, as a test piece I made had it in there pretty snug and I had to pry it out with a screwdriver.

description.text:
EXPERIMENTAL EM / Radio / Microwave Lens

This work is based on the meta-material microwave lens work done by others.

A repeating pattern of small S-and-2 shapes, in the ratios [ x : y : z ] of [ (2y / 3) : y : (y / 2) ] arranged in LAYERS, each separated by a GAP, from which a parabolic or similar segment is CUT-OUT is known to focus radio waves and microwaves experimentally.

This example meta-material was designed to fit INSIDE a wave-guide for S-Band microwave signals, BUT you can stick as many of these REPEATING elements together to get one as large as you want.

Provided are TWO models;

  1. A LAYER of meta-material.
  2. A FRAMING plate, to be placed above and below the layers to secure them.

The default is SIX(6) layers and is sized to fit into a WR-340 S-Band waveguide, as one might create for a microwave oven.
The elements can, of course, be stacked as high and as deep as you want, as the elements consist of repeating patterns..

As provided, the material will appear TRANSPARENT to electromagnetic waves (EM).

To focus the signals, the material MUST have a PARABOLIC profile cut from it, from the INPUT side.
You can do this with hand-tools on the layers in order.
Read up on this subject for more details of the shapes to cut.
If you've got this far, I'm sure you'll be able to proceed.

Basically, the process is;

  1. Print.
  2. Leave ONE(1) layer untouched.
  3. Cut remaining layers as per your 'lens' shape.
  4. Spray layers with electrically-conductive material.
  5. Assemble into non-conductive frame.
  6. Mount in application.
  7. Use.

It is possible one may be able to make one's own radio telescope, or somesuch for a microwave oven, this way....

Heck, it's a LENS for EM radiation... I'm pretty sure you can think of a use for it!

Prusa

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Fine as possible to get CRISP prints of LAYERS.

Infill:

Less than you'd imagine.

Notes:

The FRAME elements should be NON-CONDUCTING material.
The LAYER elements should be post-production painted with an ELECTRICALLY_CONDUCTIVE material, typically metallized spray paint.

The Process of Making an EM Lens from Meta-Material.
  1. Print TWO(2) of the FRAMING panels.
  2. Print SIX(6) of the meta-material LAYERS, from PLA or similar.
  3. Leave ONE(1) alone.... that's the BACK of the lens, the output side.
  4. Shape the other layers as appropriate. This is your job.
  5. SPRAY paint the LAYERS with conductive paint, preferably metallic, to make them electrically conductive.
  6. Assemble the layers in the frame.
  7. Use.
Designed over a weekend based on designs freely available on the Web, based on advanced physics research.

description.text:
This Chip-E is remixed with CL4P-TP aka Claptrap from the video game Borderlands. This gives Chip-E an even more robotic look. Besides that we have added arms to enable better dancing abilities. With his new eye (Pi-Cam) he can see and snap pictures. Speaking of it we have added a Raspberry Pi Zero, with this major hardware upgrade the possibilities are almost endless. So e.g. we changed the little piezo speaker to a real speaker, which we connected over a lowpass filter to the GPIO Pin 18 of the Pi according to adafruits instructions: “https://learn.adafruit.com/adding-basic-audio-ouput-to-raspberry-pi-zero”. So now the ChipE is capable to talk in a real Language or to play songs.
The big problem we ran into with the Raspberry is, that there aren’t enough PWM pins, which are essential for the servos. We thought about using the adafruit servo driver, but we didn't want to wait until it arrives, so we added an Arduino UNO, which communicates over I2C with the Pi and just does the PWM-Stuff for it. An Arduino Nano would be even better, because it's smaller, but we had the UNO already at home.
Of course the RobotGeek Geekduino is useable as well.
One idea was, to program a web interface for the Robot on the Raspberry, so it’s possible to control CH1P-E over your smartphone.

We wanted to use the original servos from RobotGeek, but they were hard to come by for us here in Austria, so we used MG995 servos, but we designed
the body so, that the Robotgeek servos are useable as well. We changed the shoes, feet and legs for the MG995 differently. The arms are moved by standard 9g servos. There are no ball bearings needed. The feet for the MG995 are screwed together with tapping screws.

By using the RobotGeek kit, only the Raspberry Pi stuff (pi zero, pi camera, speaker components), the servo for the arms and the tapping screws must be bought seperatly.

If you want to use the RobotGeek Servos print the part with the "_RobotGeek" ending, otherwise use the "_995" Parts.

We tried to use as many snap fits and screw connections as possible. Only the camera holder for the picam, the speakercap and the antenna must be glued in.

Currently we are in the process of programming the Robot, but we don't have enough time to complete it right now.

  • Raspberry Pi as brain
  • Arduino as PWM Controller
  • real speaker
  • Pi camera
  • HD 44870 16x2 LCD
  • LED
  • moving Arms
  • Sweet dancing moves

optional Features:

  • 1x LED

description.text:
Hello everyone, here's my humble remix of the Chip-E.

Here are the changes:

  • the body:
    • the head has been covered by compatible lego plates generated with openscad and the library from projunk
    • the base and middle received compatible technic L beams also generated with openscad and the technic L-beam library again from projunk
    • a body part has been inserted between the middle and head sections to store an arduino mega
    • every section is bound to others with compatible lego technic friction pins (the black ones)
    • it has now a nose and the head section has been elevated to receive the LCD replacement.

Now let me introduce the electronic parts:

  • the 2 lines LCDs has been replaced by 2 Nokia5110 graphic LCDs (at first, I wasn't sure at first if both could be driven separately)
  • an HC-SR04 ultrasound sensor in the middle section for obstacles avoidance and in the future SLAM(Simultaneous Localization And Mapping)
  • a HC-06 bluetooth module to use with and android phone as remote controller
    => wired on RX3 and TX3
  • the battery pack is a 2S or 7.4V
  • the servos have a 6V source
  • the Mega/screens/HC-SR04 and HC-06 are powered by a ubec also wired on the 2S pack.

While the pins on the head mostly are mostly for fun and decoration (like beautiful Skyrim helmet horns), the technic beams on the base and middle section are real strong anchors to add physic functionalities like animated arms. The Arduino mega allows also lots of other functionnalities (voltage sensor for self battery depletion detection, ...).

Some testing videos:

First tests of walking (2sec then 1 sec periods)

title: Swamp/Forest Terrain Tiles 6x6 for RPG and Wargame

description.text:
These are 29 different 6" x 6" tiles for use as swamp or forest floor tiles. Most of them have pools in them (use clear resin or epoxy to pour in the water). As shown in my finished pics, they look best if you add plants and ground clutter for variety. I advise printing with a top layer of about 1mm thick to ensure that the pool areas are water-tight, so when you pour resin or epoxy it doesn't leak through.

They are a hair thicker than most game tiles, as I wanted the pools to be deep enough to put in tiny fish prior to pouring the resin. I'm well aware that these won't print on a small, 4" x 4" printer bed. I made them for my own game table, and am sharing them to help the community. You can still shrink the X/Y down to 4x4 if you wish, the terrain will just be smaller. (You can probably leave the Z as-is if desired.)

Paint the tiles a base color (such as brown or green), and paint the rocks and trees prior to putting down any clutter grass or plants. Green will give a more vibrant, alive look to the plants. Brown will look gloomier, unless you put down such a thick layer of grass/clutter than you can't see the ground beneath at all.

The plants shown in my samples are generally from Michaels and Hobby Lobby, as are the leaves on the trees. Hot glue onto the tiles. Hot glue sets much faster and stronger than superglue, as info.

title: Welding glass to Harbor Freight goggles adapter for eclipse viewing

description.text:
This is an adapter insert to fit standard 4.25in x 2in welding glass into the plastic housing of cheap Harbor Freight welding goggles to make an eclipse viewer. Harbor Freight sells a sub-$10 2 pack of welding goggles https://www.harborfreight.com/2-piece-welding-goggles-set-35711.html, but they're only shade 10. To safely view the sun requires at least shade 14 https://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEhelp/safety.html. The solution to this is to purchase shade 14 glass from any welding supply store. Remove the plastic lenses, or flip-up lens housing and use this adapter to fit the glass to the flexible plastic goggles.

The retaining clips are fit using any small wood or plastic screw about 1/2 in long. I use the plastic screws I salvage from old HP inkjet printers, but #4 wood screws would work fine also. In disassembling the HF goggles, you need to pull the black pin out from the top of the lenses. If it breaks on the way out, print the retaining pin as a replacement.
I recommend printing in dark plastic to minimize the amount of light transmission through the printed housing.

Original design files are hosted at OnShape if you'd like to modify.

title: Vertical MKS SBASE case with Full Graphic Smart Controller

description.text:
This is a vertical case for the MKS SBase Smoothieboard clone, combined with various display cases. Good compact case for printers utilizing aluminum extrusions.

The case bottom is the same for all versions. This forms the back of the case, and holds the MKS SBase board. The others are for the "front" of the case. Depending on the display you are using, you can pick and choose which case "front" works for you.

Accepts M3 screws.

The included spacer is to move the case slightly away from the extrusion so that it does not interfere with Openbuilds wheels. You may or may not need it, depending on your configuration

The second spacer is for cases where the X-axis motor has insufficient clearance to pass the case. This occurred on my Tarantula. It prints without support if rotated 90 degrees and printed on its side.

40 MM low-profile fan recommended.

For the 12864 screen, 4 20mm M3 screws are required to secure the screen cover to the top part of the case.

I used the fan from https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00NWI8FLS/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1. 15 mm screws were just long enough to hold the fan without sticking out of the front of the case.

All other screws should be about 10mm long

Update: Alternative top for the MKS TFT28 and MKS TFT32 touch screens added. Support material recommended for the bottom side of the hole for the display.

Update 2: Added top for Raspberry Pi with 5 inch screen. An external USB cable is needed for the Raspberry Pi. It also may need to be supplied with external power. The Pi cover will require supports for the USB and network port openings

The cover for the Pi is just the front of Phil_Maddox's Pi case. If you wish, you can print his back, and have a Pi that is removable and able to be used for other purposes when not printing. I have included the back as a convenience, but take no credit for it. The original Pi case is all Phil_Maddox' work

As with Phil's work, there is no MicroUSB hole. It will have to be drilled/Dremeled if needed. I may add an option with this hole if I can find better documentation of where the hole needs to be. Seems to vary depending on the Pi version.

Thank you Phil_Maddox and gadzet28 for providing the templates I used for the Pi and the 12864, and megablue for posting the original MKS Base case.

Update: Combined TFT28 and 12864 and Combined TFT32 and 12864 smart controller option added. The 12864 top is required to cover the top. Not as compact as previous designs, but the Smart Controller has functionality that has not (yet) been added to the TFT28 and 32. Supports required. Printing with the front "down" gave me the best results.

Also added larger versions with an extended "box" underneath the panel for users that need room for additional components, such as smoothers, buck converters, adapter boards for the newer E3D cartridge thermisters, etc. These can be hard to cram into the previous cases.

No mounts are present for these boards, as they vary dramatically in size, but screw holes can be drilled, or they can be glued into place.

description.text:
I needed replacements for my mounts that were slowly deforming in my heated enclosure(40C) due to them being made from pla. Also, as is standard for Tronxy, the mounts came with warping by the threaded bushings that required me to shim. I couldn't find much out there for my P802E at the time, so I made my own. I made the motor mount extra beefy while staying within the original dims. I also added cable tie features around the bearings as my old ones had loosened up. I did not spare any plastic when I printed my mounts. I did 4 walls and 70% infill with abs. Yes, that infill was way overkill. Supports are built in. Obviously, you will need to orient them so the anchoring discs are on the bed. I did tweak the motor clearance hole after printing mine to a teardrop shape as it was a little messy there.

On the right side I made a belt tensioner that hugs the ouside of the mount and is adjusted via 4 screws. Yeah, a lot of tensioners use just one or two screws, but four is nice and stable and you rarely have to tighten. This will work with the original mounts as well. You reuse all the original hardware plus four m3 screws and nuts. Prints without support though you may need to do a little cleanup in the countersinks. I should have angled those. Maybe I will fix that eventually. 20% infill is plenty for this part. Print with the right end side down. -Not the orientation that it comes in as.

UPDATE: 9-16-2017
Added a file for a x-tensioner with a geared idler pulley. Uses a GT2 20 teeth pulley with a 5mm bore. This helps reduce belt vibration.

Tronxy p802e

Notes:

Use a generous brim if using abs.

Flexing the discs toward the part should crack them off pretty clean. Can clean up with knife, file or instrument of choice if you want after that. Supports on motor mount break away fairly well with just a bit of exacto work needed. The fit around the idler on the tensioner part is supposed to be snug. You may need to file slightly if you have a little extra material. You install the idler parts by putting in the screw a little past the opening and adding the first flat washer - then thread the screw a little past the washer and then stack in the bearing and so on. Its a bit awkward, but very doable with patience and a steady hand.

description.text:
This project began as a prototype & then manufacturing service for Yuni (http://www.yuniheadphones.com/), which is attempting to build a set of stereo headphones for people with unilateral hearing loss. The Yuni has two distinct ear cups; one with two speakers in them angled at the ear to preserve separation of L/R channels, and one dummy cup with nothing in it. This version, called the Duli, is this original project adapted for un-impaired dual-hearing use (standard headphones).
Yunis can be purchased from the link, but Dulis are not yet for sale (until we're completely caught up on the Yunis!)
But as always, other stuff IS for sale in our Etsy :)
https://www.etsy.com/shop/CarryTheWhat
And we do actually have a 'vitamin kit' with all the non-printed parts you will need here: https://www.tindie.com/products/CarryTheWhat/duli-headphones-vitamin-kit/

NOTE: to make this a little easier, I have put together a listing on Tindie to ship the full kit of vitamins together:
https://www.tindie.com/products/CarryTheWhat/duli-headphones-vitamin-kit/
Vitamin Bill Of Materials:
  • Speaker drivers x2 -- $8.76 via digikey
  • Foam ear pads x2 -- $5.49 via amazon
  • 1/8th inch jacks x2 $3.00 via radioshack
  • 1/8th inch y-cable $4.39 via we-supply
    There definitely could be better deals than these, and you can reduce the material cost buying in bulk. But buying piecemeal, the full vitamin BOM should cost about $22, plus whatever shipping. And then of course the plastic for the printed parts.
    Printed Bill of Materials:
  • earcover_cap x2
  • earcover x2
  • pin1 x4 (to join earcover to earcover_caps)
  • pin2 x2 (to join earcover cup unit to headband)
    EITHER
  • headband_full
    OR
  • headband_half x2
  • headband_join
    There are two types of headbands here, and it's because the headbands are quite large prints. Originally, it was designed to fit on the Replicator 1. So the headband was split and printed in halves, joined by a dovetail joint. But these were not coming out consistent, so we have switched to printing the headband in one full go on a Rostock Max.
    The headband is not adjustable, so if you find the fit to be too small or two large, you can export a different size. If you need any help with the OpenSCAD just let me know!
    Assembly:
    You will need 4 small lengths of wire, with at least the ends stripped. You will need to do just a tad of soldering... connecting the 1/8th inch jacks to their respective speaker drivers. Both things have a polarity to mind -- on the back of the speaker driver there are two pre-soldered pads. The one on the right has a red dot, indicating that it is positive.

description.text:
A quick jig developed to test the thrust from different propeller blades. It was designed to be uses with kitchen scales as the measuring device. The reading on the scales (weight) simply must be divided by 3 for a true thrust measurement. That weight can then be divided by gravity 9.8m/s/s to achieve thrust in Newtons. Equation found below;
Force(N)= Weight(kg) / (3*Gravity),
assuming gravity is roughly equal to 10 (9.81 for more precision)
Force(N)= Weight(kg) / 30
If you want to know how much the propeller/ motor combo can lift, don't divide by gravity;
Lift capability(kg) = Weight(kg) / 3
As this jig uses kitchen scales the values calculated may not be super accurate however it will give a good ballpark figure, perfect for testing 3D printed propellers.

description.text:
I could not find a fan mount suitable for my dual extruder, so I designed this one.

You need to print 3 pieces to use the fan mount: the base, arm and fan mount. The included STL files have fan mounts that fit 40 and 60mm fans in dual or single fan configurations. The arms are varying length to give you some choices in how to construct the mount. Note that by design, the fans shake back and forth slightly (especially with longer arm). If you are looking for something that seems more sturdy, you may want to lock it down somehow or use the scad script to print a thicker arm or connection piece. I happen to like the fan movement.

  • The base is designed for m5 screws.
  • The arm uses m3 screws and lock nuts.
  • The 40mm fan mount uses m3 screws. The 60mm fan mount has m4.5 screws (m3 screws work just fine).

For further customization, the OpenSCAD script I wrote to generate these STL files is on GitHub. It is parametric and should be fairly easy to use: https://github.com/adgaudio/3dPrinter/blob/master/random_parts/fan_dual_mount.scad

title: Medical ID Bracelet (Parametric)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a configurable, parametric medical ID wristband that includes the Star of Life (with Rod of Asclepius) and a short message on either side to help advertise a medial condition that the wearer has. In the photo, the bracelet says "ALLERGIC" on one side and "TREE NUTS" on the other, but any combination of the following may be easily selected: ALLERGIC, ALLERGY, AUTISM, BEE/WASP, CHRONIC, DAIRY, DIABETES, EGG, INSULIN, LATEX, MILD, PEANUT, PENICILLIN, SEAFOOD, SEVERE, TREE NUTS, WHEAT.
The bracelet itself is also configurable. Just measure the width and thickness of the wearer's wrist, and tweak the sizes and characteristics of the band, star, and text, and the OpenSCAD file will render both the flat wristband, and a wrist form that you can use to shape the wrist band for a perfect fit.

1) Extract the files into a single directory and open with OpenSCAD. 2) Tweak the parameters below, render, and print. The default settings display "ALLERGIC" and "TREE NUTS" and is sized to fit my five year old. 3) Secure the flat bracelet to the wrist form so that the Star of Life is in the middle, and carefully heat and bend the bracelet around on both sides. I've had success heating the bracelet while rolling over it on a desk. 4) Paint or use a Sharpie to color the background of the Star of Life, and the fronts of the letters for better visibility. Wrist-related parameters
  • wristWidth: The width of the wrist (side to side, wider than thickness)
  • wristThickness: The thickness of the wrist (top to bottom)
  • play: Millimeters of "play" to be added to wrist -- so it's not too tight
    • Wristband-related parameters
  • bandLength: The total length of the wristband, or zero to calculate automatically
  • bandWidth: The width of the band (excluding the cross)
  • bandThickness: The thickness of the band (excluding text and cross)
  • borderWidth: The width of the band border, inside which the text is placed
  • textThickness: The thickness of the text
  • textVOverlap: The distance the text overlaps the border on the top and bottom
    • Star of Life-related parameters
  • starSize: The size (height/width) of the Star of Life
  • starHeight: The thickness of the Star of Life
  • starSymbolEmboss: The distance the Rod of Asclepius symbol is embossed
    • Parameters related to the printed text
  • leftText: The text option from the list below to show on the left
  • rightText: The text option from the list below to show to the right
    • Currently you define any two of the following: ALLERGIC, ALLERGY, AUTISM, BEE/WASP, CHRONIC, DAIRY, DIABETES, EGG, INSULIN, LATEX, MILD, PEANUT, PENICILLIN, SEAFOOD, SEVERE, TREE NUTS, WHEAT Rendering options
  • includeWristForm: Whether or not to render the wrist form
  • includeWristBand: Whether or not to render the wrist band
  • distanceApart: Render the objects this distance apart
